terviews, this book provides the first comprehensive analysis of the history of the German returnees, explored as a historyof memory, both during Germany's division and after unification. At its core lies the question of how the experiences of war captivity were transformed into individual and collective memories. The book argues that memory of the experience of captivity and return is complex and multilayered and has been shaped by postwar political and social frameworks. Christiane Wienand is a historian and works in Heidelberg, Germany. She holds a PhD in Historyfrom University College London.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollective memoryzGermany. 0aEx-prisoners of warxHistoryy20th centuryzGermany. 0aEx-prisoners of warzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPrisoners and prisons. 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aDivided Germany.  aFormer Prisoners of War.  aGerman History.  aMemory.  aPOWs.  aPostwar Germany.  aReunited Germany.  aWorld War II.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782045304?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782045304423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782045304/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles